==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*wenda-'', originally ‘to make something twist or wind’, a causative form of ''*winda-'' ‘to wreathe, twist’ (Old English [[windan]], English [[wind]]).  Cognate with Old Frisian [[wenda]], Old Saxon [[wendian]], Old High German [[wentan]] (Dutch & German [[wenden]]), Old Norse [[venda]] (Swedish [[vända]]), Gothic [[𐍅𐌰𐌽𐌳𐌾𐌰𐌽]].

===Pronunciation===
[[IPA]]: /'wendan/

===Verb===
'''wendan''' (class 1 weak)
# ''(transitive)'' to [[turn]] or change position
# to change direction (of)
# ''(transitive & intransitive)'' to [[change]] or [[alter]]
# ''(instransitive)'' to [[go]] or [[depart]]
# to take place or [[happen]]

